Main ergonomic changes to make API cleaner and easy to use.

- directly use ptr in operator->
- Remove the positional constructor of PassContext in C++, instead allow the creation of a default one and mutate the corresponding fields. (This allows arguments to be explicit, like keyword arguments). This is done given that we might grow the PassContext in the future.
```c++
 auto ctx = PassContext::Create();
 ctx->opt_level = 2;
 ctx->fallback_device = kDLCPU;
  With<PassContext> scope(ctx);
  // pass context in effect.
```
- Add overload of operator() to Pass as well, so we can directly do seq(mod)
- Remove LOG(INFO), use ```DLOG(INFO)``` for debug logging

We have quite a few RAII style scope context throughout the code base, and their naming conventions are not very consistent. This PR aims to provide a unified API for the RAII scoping similar to python's with syntax.

Any context class needs to implement set of standard functions to be implemented by a context class, which implement two functions(EnterWithScope, ExitWithScope) and then we can create an RAII class With<ContextType>.

```c++
{
   With<Target> target_scope(target);;
   // target in effect
}
{ 
   With<ConstraintContext> constraint(&analyzer, x % 3 == 0);
   // constraint in effect.
}
```
- Refactored Target, BuildConfig, ConstraintContext to use the new style.
- Renamed BuildConfig::create -> BuildConfig::Create to be consistent with the style
- Use Target::Current() to indicate the current thread local scope context.

While trying to eliminate nats from the tuple, I encountered a bug in the autodiff tests that appeared to be due to global variables not being eliminated from the gradient and having the types fail to match.

I attempt to address that error here by having global vars eliminated from the gradient and inlining them using a let binding to ensure recursion can still be preserved. However, I'm getting some weird errors here that I think may be due to other parts of AD: I notice free variables ending up in the gradient where they shouldn't and got a type error I could not make sense of.

